<main>
  <h1 id="title"> Mac Miller</h1>
  
  <div id="img-div">
    <img src="https://www.rollingstone.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/mac-miller-left-behind.jpg" id="img">
    <div id="img-caption">One week before his death, a happy Mac Miller.</div>
    </div>
<div id="tribute-info">  
  <div> <strong>Here's a time line of Mac Miller's career:</strong></div>
  </div>
<div id="list">
  <ul>
       <li> 2007 - Miller began his career in Pittsburgh's hip hop scene at the age of fifteen.</li>
  <li> 2010 - He signed a record deal with independent label Rostrum Records, and released his breakthrough mixtapes K.I.D.S.   </li>
    <li> 2011 - He released Best Day Ever Miller's debut studio album, Blue Slide Park, which became the first independently-distributed debut album to top the US Billboard 200 since 1995.   </li>
        <li>2013 - He founded the record label imprint REMember Music.   </li>
        <li> 2014 - After his second studio album, Watching Movies with the Sound Off , he left Rostrum and signed with the major label Warner Bros. Records.    </li>
        <li>2015 - He realeased the album  GO:OD AM    </li>
        <li>2016 - He realeased the album The Divine Feminine.   </li>
        <li>2018 - He realeased the album Swimming.</li>
        <li>Posthumous 2020 - He realeased the album Circles. For Swimming, he was posthumously nominated for a Grammy Award for Best Rap Album.     </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div id="bottom">
He also served as a record producer for various artists, including himself, under the pseudonym Larry Fisherman.
      Miller struggled with substance abuse, which was often referenced in his lyrics. On September 7, 2018, Miller died from an accidental drug overdose of cocaine, fentanyl, and alcohol at his home, aged 26.
  </div>
 <div id="quote"><em>“They’re gonna try to tell you no, shatter all your dreams. But you gotta get up, and go and think of better things.”</em> - Mac Miller </div>
  <div id="tribute-link">If you have time, you should read more about this incredible human being on his
    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mac_Miller">Wikipedia entry</a>.</div>
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
